<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#Aerial> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Aerial"@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#Aquatic
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#Aquatic> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#Aquatic> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#RealWorldPlace> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#Aquatic> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "A physical habitat located in or around bodies of water, such as oceans, rivers, or lakes."@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#Aquatic> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#BiologicalModule> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#Aquatic> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Aquatic"@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#AscensionalSymbol
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#AscensionalSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#AscensionalSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#AscensionalSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#ImaginarySymbol> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#AscensionalSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SchizomorphicStructure> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SchizomorphicStructure> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#AscensionalSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#inScheme> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DurandImaginary> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DurandImaginary> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#AscensionalSymbol> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#belongsTo> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SchizomorphicStructure> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#AscensionalSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Ascensional symbol embodies heroic symbols of elevation, verticality, and transcendence. It represents the upward movement to escape the degradation of time and the symbolic refusal of death. In this structure, height is synonymous with the pure and the divine; the wing is the ascensional instrument that contradicts gravity. These symbols manifest a quest to regain lost power through movement toward metaphysical spaces (e.g., mountains), dazzling imagery (arrows, wings), and virile archetypes of celestial royalty and the warrior."@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#AscensionalSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SymbolicModule> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#AscensionalSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Ascensional Symbol"@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#AscensionalSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Ascensional Symbol"@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#BiologicalModule
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#BiologicalModule> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#BiologicalModule> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#Module> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#BiologicalModule> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "The Biological Module catalogs the physical and behavioural traits of creatures — whether real or imaginary — as described in Bestiaries and other Sources. It distinguishes real animals from imaginary beings, and further classifies the latter into composite and hybrid creatures whose anatomy is derived from two or more biological sources. For real animals it documents deformities and monstrous irregularities through a structured vocabulary of anatomical anomaly: absence of a canonical part, duplication, and modification. For imaginary beings it records the anatomical parts they possess and the real animals, plants, or inanimate elements from which those parts are derived. Across all creatures the module captures habitats — distinguishing real geographic environments from mythological or imaginary spaces — diets, and abilities. This layer serves as the primary morphological record that the Symbolic Module then interprets as archetypal and cultural meaning."@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#BiologicalModule> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Biological Module"@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#Carnivorous
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#Carnivorous> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#Carnivorous> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#Diet> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#Carnivorous> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "A diet consisting primarily of animal meat."@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#Carnivorous> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#BiologicalModule> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#Carnivorous> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Carnivorous"@en .
