# https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#CatamorphicSymbol
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#CatamorphicSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#CatamorphicSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#CatamorphicSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#ImaginarySymbol> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#CatamorphicSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SchizomorphicStructure> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#CatamorphicSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#inScheme> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DurandImaginary> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#CatamorphicSymbol> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#belongsTo> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SchizomorphicStructure> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#CatamorphicSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Catamorphic symbol embodies falling, gravity, and the physical degradation of flesh. These dynamic images of transience represent the dazzling acceleration of time during a downward plunge. Catamorphic symbol captures the existential anxiety of the fall, where movement signifies the inescapable and rapid passage of time toward death."@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#CatamorphicSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SymbolicModule> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#CatamorphicSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Catamorphic Symbol"@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#CatamorphicSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Catamorphic Symbol"@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#CyclicalSymbol
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#CyclicalSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#CyclicalSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#CyclicalSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#ImaginarySymbol> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#CyclicalSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SyntheticStructure> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SyntheticStructure> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#CyclicalSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#inScheme> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DurandImaginary> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#CyclicalSymbol> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#belongsTo> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SyntheticStructure> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#CyclicalSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Cyclical symbol represents the archetype of the Eternal Return and time as a series of phases. Using the moon as a primary model - being the first to die and the first to be reborn - these symbols suggest that time is a series of phases where opposites (life/death, light/dark) coexist. This 'lunar optimism' does not negate death but reintegrates it as an essential stage of an incessant, evolving movement where every sunset is a prelude to a new dawn. The repetition of opposites is also linked to evolution: it is not merely a continuous repetition of the same events. Things that change may also evolve or move forward; they may progress."@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#CyclicalSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SymbolicModule> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#CyclicalSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Cyclical Symbol"@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#CyclicalSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Cyclical Symbol"@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DiareticSymbol
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DiareticSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DiareticSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DiareticSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#ImaginarySymbol> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DiareticSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SchizomorphicStructure> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DiareticSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#inScheme> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DurandImaginary> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DiareticSymbol> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#belongsTo> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SchizomorphicStructure> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DiareticSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Diaretic symbol embodies figures of cutting, weapons, and purification, derived from the Greek term 'diairesis' (division). They represent the human need for analysis, categorization, and absolute separation to overcome natural chaos. The hero's weapon is a dual symbol of power and purity; by cutting through confusion and separating the real from the imaginary, or good from evil, the hero gains mastery over the world. In this structure, the act of separation is the primary source of intellectual and spiritual power."@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DiareticSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SymbolicModule> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DiareticSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Diaretic Symbol"@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DiareticSymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Diaretic Symbol"@en .
# 
# https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DiurnalRegime
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DiurnalRegime> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DiurnalRegime> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#Concept> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DiurnalRegime> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#Regime> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#Regime> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DiurnalRegime> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#inScheme> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DurandImaginary> .
# 
# https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DurandImaginary
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DurandImaginary> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#ConceptScheme> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DurandImaginary> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#hasTopConcept> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#ImaginaryStructure> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#ImaginaryStructure> <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type> <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DurandImaginary> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#hasTopConcept> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#Regime> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DurandImaginary> <http://purl.org/dc/terms/title> "Durand's structures of the Imaginary"@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DurandImaginary> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "A conceptual scheme providing a framework for the symbolic and anthropological analysis of creatures within bestiaries. It acts as the theoretical pivot of the Symbolic Module, allowing for the classification of beasts and their attributes based on their relationship with human anxiety regarding time and death. By applying Gilbert Durand's regimes and structures defined in 'Les Structures Anthropologiques de l'Imaginaire', 'beast' can map how physical biological traits - such as wings - serve as archetypal responses to mortality, transforming the creature from a mere biological entity into a profound cultural symbol."@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DurandImaginary> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SymbolicModule> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DurandImaginary> <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#wasDerivedFrom> "Durand, G. (1972). Le Strutture Antropologiche dell'Immaginario: introduzione all'archetipologia generale" .
# 
