# #################################################################
# #
# #    Annotations
# #
# #################################################################
# 
# 
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DiurnalRegime> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "The Diurnal Regime is characterized by the battle against death and time. It is governed by antithesis, encompassing axiomatic images that give rise to two polarized facets: a background of darkness against which the victorious splendor of light is contrasted, and antithetical reconquest of negative values. It embodies the sharp logic of the sword and heroic battles against the passage of time. This regime is built upon schizomorphic structures, defined by separation, fall, antithesis, and scission. It is a multifaceted regime that includes theriomorphic, nyctomorphic, catamorphic, ascensional, spectacular, and diaretic symbols. Together, these symbols express both the profound anxiety in front of time and death and the heroic drive to transcend or overcome these forces."@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DiurnalRegime> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SymbolicModule> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DiurnalRegime> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Diurnal Regime"@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#DiurnalRegime> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Diurnal Regime"@en .
# 
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#ImaginaryStructure> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "The structural framework of the imaginary as defined by Gilbert Durand in 'Les Structures Anthropologiques de l'Imaginaire', acting as the mediating layer between biological reflexes and symbolic expression. It represents the archetypal logic that organizes a creature's physical and behavioral attributes into a coherent symbolic system. It provides the protocol through which raw sensory data - such as a beast's fangs, its flight, or its habitat - is transformed into a structured symbolic response (Schizomorphic, Mystical, or Synthetic) to the existential anxiety of time and death."@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#ImaginaryStructure> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SymbolicModule> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#ImaginaryStructure> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Imaginary Structure"@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#ImaginaryStructure> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Imaginary Structure"@en .
# 
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#ImaginarySymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "The shared OWL class and intermediate SKOS concept grouping all specific symbolic categories recognised by Gilbert Durand within his structures of the imaginary. As an owl:Class it provides the common type for all symbol individuals (TeriomorphicSymbol, AscensionalSymbol, CyclicalSymbol, etc.), allowing properties such as :belongsTo to range over them uniformly. As a skos:Concept it sits between :ImaginaryStructure and the specific symbol individuals in the DurandImaginary thesaurus, making the three-level hierarchy (ImaginaryStructure → ImaginarySymbol → specific symbol) navigable via skos:broader."@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#ImaginarySymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SymbolicModule> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#ImaginarySymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Imaginary Symbol"@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#ImaginarySymbol> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Imaginary Symbol"@en .
# 
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#MysticalStructure> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Mystical structures include symbols of intimacy and calm, the search for light within darkness. The principles underlying mystical structures are analogy and similarity. Instead of battling against time, one enters into union with it. The mind takes images of terror and rewrites them positively, transforming them into refuge and protected space. Within this logic, opposites can coexist. In mystical structures one finds doubling and adherence rather than antithesis. It functions through inversion, doubling, and adherence, turning the devouring mouth of the diurnal regime into a protective container."@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#MysticalStructure> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SymbolicModule> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#MysticalStructure> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Mystical Structure (or Antiphrastic)"@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#MysticalStructure> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#altLabel> "Antiphrastic"@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#MysticalStructure> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Mystical Structure"@en .
# 
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#NocturnalRegime> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "The Nocturnal Regime represents an attitude of reconciliation in front of the fleeting nature of time, incorporating symbols of transformation and cyclicality. The symbols belonging to the nocturnal regime exorcise fear by transforming images into reassuring figures. Unlike the diurnal regime, the antidote to the passing of time is not sought on a superhuman or transcendent level, but rather in reassuring intimacy or in the rhytmic constants that govern natural phenomena. The nocturnal regime is divided into synthetic structures and mystical structures."@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#NocturnalRegime> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SymbolicModule> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#NocturnalRegime> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Nocturnal Regime"@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#NocturnalRegime> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Nocturnal Regime"@en .
# 
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#Regime> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "The fundamental high-level classification of Durand, organized around sensory-motor dominants (postural, digestive, cyclic). Regimes act as organizational systems of the imagination, condensing multiple symbolic meanings into a coherent structure."@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#Regime> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SymbolicModule> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#Regime> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Regime"@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#Regime> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Regime"@en .
# 
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SchizomorphicStructure> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "The Schizomorphic Structure represents the mode of the imaginary governed by the Diurnal Regime. It functions through the principles of antithesis and verticality as a defensive response to the anxiety of time. It operates via 'diaresis' – the act of cutting, dividing, and establishing absolute distinctions to maintain the separation between light and dark, height and depth. This structure organizes symbols into two polarized groups: the 'symbols of the antithesis' (teriomorphic, nyctomorphic, and catamorphic), which represent the terror of the abyss and devouring time; and the 'symbols of transcendence' (ascensional, spectacular, and diaretic), which provide the tools for the heroic reconquest through verticality, solar vision, and the purifying sword."@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SchizomorphicStructure> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SymbolicModule> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SchizomorphicStructure> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Schizomorphic Structure (or Heroic)"@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SchizomorphicStructure> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Schizomorphic Structure (or Heroic)"@en .
# 
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SyntheticStructure> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Synthetic structure operates by bringing contradictions into dialogue and includes cyclical symbols. It treats time as a series of phases, where night is a necessary prelude to dawn and death is a prelude to rebirth. It transforms the fall into a slow, controlled descent, allowing for the acceptance of change and progress through the succession of opposites."@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SyntheticStructure> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SymbolicModule> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SyntheticStructure> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Synthetic Structure (or Dramatic)"@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SyntheticStructure> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#altLabel> "Dramatic"@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SyntheticStructure> <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel> "Synthetic Structure"@en .
# 
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#hasDistinctiveTrait> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Records a short, characterizing description of the most defining features of a creature. It captures a headline characterization rather than the structured anatomical, dietary, or symbolic data modelled elsewhere."@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#hasDistinctiveTrait> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#BiologicalModule> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#hasDistinctiveTrait> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "has distinctive trait"@en .
# 
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#hasDivergence> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "The parent property for all divergence assertions linking a source-specific Interpretation to the biological feature — either an AnatomicalPart or an Ability — that differs from the creature's canonical description in that Source. Subproperties :additionalAbility, :removedAbility, :additionalPart, and :removedPart specialise the nature of the divergence. This structure allows the ontology to answer questions such as 'which interpretations add wings to a normally wingless creature' or 'which sources suppress a creature's canonical venom ability'."@en .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#hasDivergence> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#isDefinedBy> <https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#SymbolicModule> .
<https://w3id.org/beast/ontology#hasDivergence> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "has divergence"@en .
